for (InputSplit split : splits) {
     TableSplit tableSplit = (TableSplit) split;
     assertTrue(tableSplit.getScanAsString().isEmpty());
 }

In table split code, add this...

public String getScanAsString() {
   return scan;
 }

Run this test
  @Test
  public void testGetSplits() throws IOException, InterruptedException, ClassNotFoundException {
    testNumOfSplits(1, 26);
    testNumOfSplits(3, 78);  <====
  }

If number of splits per region is > 1, your patch didn't handle the TableSplit constructor in this call createNInputSplitsUniform(). Your test still passes because you are asserting on a default Scan object and not the fact that it shouldn't be set in the first place.

